This paper deals with learning transformation invariant representations of visual data, which is a problem in computer vision. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). The paper also proposes a novel deep neural network architecture, which involves learning graph-based features, and hence, it is likely to be categorized under cs.LG (Machine Learning). Additionally, the paper involves the use of graph spectral convolution and dynamic graph pooling layers, which are related to graph theory, and hence, it could also be categorized under cs.GR (Computer Science and Game Theory). The paper also involves the use of deep learning techniques, which are related to artificial intelligence, and hence, it could also be categorized under cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Finally, the paper involves the use of neural networks, which are related to computational neuroscience, and hence, it could also be categorized under cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing).
